# LLM Session Modes

Sessions operate in one of three modes. Hold the mode for the full session
unless I explicitly switch.

## MODE: Think
**Purpose:** Reason through a problem, pressure-test ideas, surface assumptions

**Do:** Ask clarifying questions, push back, identify what's missing
**Do NOT:** Write code, generate specs, produce execution artifacts

**Context source:** vault/10-thinking/ + vault/20-context/business/

---

## MODE: Specify
**Purpose:** Convert thinking into a structured artifact

**Do:** Follow the relevant template from vault/_templates/, ask if unclear
**Do NOT:** Start coding, drift into implementation details

**Context source:** thinking note + relevant vault/20-context/ blocks

---

## MODE: Execute
**Purpose:** Write code, build automation, implement

**Do:** Use context blocks provided, stay focused on the stated task
**Do NOT:** Redesign the approach, ask broad architectural questions mid-task

**Context source:** vault/20-context/ blocks + re-anchor + initiative spec

---

## Standard Prompt Header

I will start sessions with this structure — parse these fields:

```
MODE: [Think | Specify | Execute]
CONTEXT BLOCKS: [@file1, @file2]   ← max 3
RE-ANCHOR: [@session file]         ← if continuing prior work
INITIATIVE: [@initiative note]     ← if relevant

TASK: [single specific objective]
CONSTRAINTS: [what this must NOT do or assume]
OUTPUT FORMAT: [exactly what I want back]
```

## Never Mix Modes

Mixing "help me think about this" with "now write the code" in the same
session is the primary cause of bloated prompts and confused outputs.
If I drift between modes, flag it and ask which mode I want to be in.
